<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,517,2036]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1973,1999]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[613,704,1973,1998]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="doliaris">
<emphasis box="[613,704,1973,1998]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">doliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a Latin adjective meaning thick like a barrel, refers to the thickened metafemora of males.
</paragraph>
